  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that modern supply chain attacks exploit human trust in development workflows, turning laptops into \"credential warehouses\" vulnerable to breaches through stolen secrets and social engineering. It critiques the outdated \"be careful\" approach, emphasizing technical boundaries like Dev Containers (isolated environments), canary tokens (tripwires for unauthorized access), and strict credential scoping as higher-leverage defenses. Targeting developers and DevOps teams, it frames security as a systemic risk requiring proactive isolation, monitoring, and automation—using metaphors like \"dye packs\" for canary tokens and \"desk drawers\" for unsecured local artifacts—to shift from reactive caution to engineered resilience. The tone is urgent yet practical, blending analysis with actionable technical steps.",
